UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85072517896&doi=10.1021%2facsmacrolett.9b00532&partnerID=40&md5=f93a1a5d711e8de1913d7ac49fa2c134
AB  - We recently reported a coarse-grained simulation study of the effect of host polymer polarity on ionic transport in polymer electrolytes. In the code responsible for the conductivity calculations, all cationic (c) and anionic (a) charges (q = qc = -qa) were incorrectly assigned a value of 9.0, instead of 9.836, derived from the following equation (Formula Presented) where e is the proton charge, ?0 is the permittivity of free space, e is the Lennard-Jones characteristic energy (5.27 × 10-21 J),1 and s is the Lennard-Jones characteristic distance (4.5 Å).1 Such an error resulted in both the Nernst-Einstein and true ionic conductivities calculated initially in this work being uniformly reduced by a factor of (9.836/9)2 = 1.19. In Figure 1A, we display the old Nernst-Einstein and true ionic conductivities. Such data can be found in figures 1 and 2 of the original text. In Figure 1B, we plot the properly scaled Nernst-Einstein and true ionic conductivities. One can see that the behavior of the data remains qualitatively the same; however, we note that the rescaled conductivities are slightly (Figure Presented) higher than the old values due to the rescaling mentioned above. © 2019 American Chemical Society.
