UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-0035335078&doi=10.1007%2fs12043-001-0086-9&partnerID=40&md5=0291945d8bcf8b862f5fe7e536ea1da9
AB  - A one-dimensional stability transport code has been developed to simulate the evolution of tokamak plasma discharges. Explicit finite-difference methods have been used to follow the temporal evolution of the electron temperature equation. The poloidal field diffusion equation nas been solved at every time step. The effects of MHD instabilities have been incorporated by solving equations for MHD mixing and tearing modes as and when required. The code has been applied to follow the evolution of tokamak plasma discharges obtained in the Saha Institute of Nuclear Physics (SINP) tokamak. From these simulations, we have been able to identify the possible models of thermal conductivity, diffusion and impurity contents in these discharges. Effects of different MHD modes have been estimated. It has been found that in low qa discharge m = 1, n = 1 and m = 2, n = 1 modes play major role in discharge evolution. These modes are found to result in the positive jump in the loop voltage which was also observed in the experiments. Hollow current density profile jφ and negative shear in the q profile have also been found in the rising phase of a discharge.
