UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-3342915055&partnerID=40&md5=b531a3a7e4b854ed82a55233a685c67e
AB  - The Waste Isolation Pilot Plant (WIPP) is a research and development facility intended to demonstrate the safe disposal of transuranic (TRU) waste generated by US Department of Energy (DOE) defense programs. Before permanently disposing of TRU waste at the WIPP, the DOE must demonstrate compliance with applicable long-term disposal standards of the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA). These disposal standards have been promulgated as Federal Regulations 40 CFR 191, Subparts B and C, and 40 CFR 194. The demonstration of compliance is achieved through an analysis of Performance Assessment which: (a) identifies the processes and events that might affect the disposal system, (b) examines the effects of these processes and events on the disposal system; and (c) estimates the overall probability distribution of cumulative releases of radionuclides caused by all significant postulated processes and events. Performance Assessment presents results of the most probable outcomes for the disposal system over the 10 000 year regulatory period, and compares the calculated radionuclide releases to probabilistic radionuclide release limits prescribed in section 191.13 of 40 CFR 191. The Sandia National Laboratories (SNL) WIPP project has been providing scientific research and development support to the DOE during the last two decades, including development of computer codes which model Performance Assessment. These include computer codes used to simulate processes within the repository system, transport and retardation of radionuclides and other hazardous materials from the repository through surrounding hydrogeologic formations, and simulation of releases due to possible future human intrusion into the repository. Probabilistic modelling and analysis codes are also used to accommodate both the uncertainty of physical parameters and the unpredictability of future events. The software QA requirement in rule 40 CFR 194 states that the models and computer codes used to support any application for certification of compliance shall be fully and clearly documented in a manner that complies with the requirement of NQA-2 Part 2.7 (abbreviated hereafter as Part 2.7). The SNL WIPP project has developed and implemented procedures to meet the requirements of Part 2.7 for Software Quality Assurance (SQA). The key elements of Part 2.7 include the concept of software development, software verification and validation, configuration management control, documentation, and verification reviews. This paper will discuss (a) the background of NQA requirements as applied to nuclear facilities (e.g. nuclear reactors), (b) how Part 2.7 SQA requirements are implemented for WIPP software, and (c) how we address the issue of validation, as required by Part 2.7, on models that predict repository performance for 10 000 years. Computer codes that model the hydrology and geology of the WIPP repository system will be used as examples for the discussion. This paper will be of particular interest to those researchers whose theoretical formulations may be used in licensing of future waste repositories.
